   {:e #blake3 "9d91180a2c331c8c9a7500de6db31fcb4666164b11dc363fc8c7722e9fcafba3" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :recon/trace-51ce6d9a0eea9f1a; DOG-FOODING ASSESSMENT (Session 029): After 38+ tasks executed using braid as the system of record, here is what works well and what needs improvement. WHAT WORKS: (1) The harvest/seed cycle genuinely prevents knowledge loss — I can resume from prior session context without manual re-explanation. (2) R(t) routing consistently recommends high-impact tasks, reducing decision paralysis. (3) The observe→crystallize→task pipeline is natural and forces me to formalize my thinking before coding. (4) TSV output (just implemented) is already saving context tokens — I can do braid task list --format tsv | awk instead of JSON+Python. (5) The reconciliation system caught phantom spec refs (INV-GUIDANCE-024/025) that would have caused structural bugs. WHAT NEEDS IMPROVEMENT: (1) The biggest friction is CEREMONY vs VELOCITY — when I'm in flow implementing code, stopping to run braid observe feels like a context switch that breaks concentration. The Zero-Cost Methodology EPIC addresses this but isn't implemented yet. (2) Task titles are too long — even with short_title, the BACKGROUND sections bloat the store. Task-as-ACP (structured task entities) would fix this. (3) The reconciliation engine's lexical similarity misses obvious connections (TSV↔ACP). spec_graph_neighbors (just implemented) should fix this but needs real-world validation. (4) F(S) is stuck at 0.67-0.68 — it doesn't respond noticeably to the work being done. The metric feels disconnected from actual progress. This may be because the V component (validation) requires more witness data to move. (5) The budget system's pyramid compression is better than truncation but still lossy — the ideal is the compile-to-prompt approach where every token is intentionally placed." :op :assert}
